SIMPLE: win
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Win
<hw>Win</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Won</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>Obs.</mark>
<conjf>Wan</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Winning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>winnen</ets>, AS.
<ets>winnan</ets> to strive, labor, fight, endure; akin to OFries.
<ets>winna</ets>, OS. <ets>winnan</ets>, D. <ets>winnen</ets> to win,
gain, G. ge<ets>winnen</ets>, OHG. <ets>winnan</ets> to strive,
struggle, Icel. <ets>vinna</ets> to labor, suffer, win, Dan.
<ets>vinde</ets> to win, Sw. <ets>vinna</ets>, Goth. <ets>winnan</ets>
to suffer, Skr. <ets>van</ets> to wish, get, gain, conquer. ⟦root⟧138.
Cf. <er>Venerate</er>, <er>Winsome</er>, <er>Wish</er>, <er>Wont</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To gain by superiority in competition or contest; to
obtain by victory over competitors or rivals; <as>as, to <ex>win</ex>
the prize in a gate; to <ex>win</ex> money; to <ex>win</ex> a battle, or
to <ex>win</ex> a country.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧This city for to
<xex>win</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Who thus shall Canaan
<xex>win</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy well-breathed horse⟦br⟧
Impels the flying car, and <qex>wins</qex> the course.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To allure to kindness; to bring to compliance; to
gain or obtain, as by solicitation or courtship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy virtue <qex>wan</qex> me; with virtue preserve me.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She is a woman; therefore to be <qex>won</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To gain over to one's side or party; to obtain the
favor, friendship, or support of; to render friendly or approving;
<as>as, to <ex>win</ex> an enemy; to <ex>win</ex> a jury</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To come to by toil or effort; to reach; to
overtake.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Even in the porch he him did <qex>win</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And when the stony path began,⟦br⟧
By which the naked peak they <qex>wan</qex>,⟦br⟧
Up flew the snowy ptarmigan.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>To extract, as ore or
coal.</def> <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To gain; get; procure; earn. See
<er>Gain</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Win</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Win
<hw>Win</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To gain the victory; to be
successful; to triumph; to prevail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor is it aught but just⟦br⟧
That he, who in debate of truth hath <qex>won</qex>,⟦br⟧
should <qex>win</qex> in arms.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To win of</b></col>, <cd>to be conqueror over.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>To win on</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>To win upon</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
gain favor or influence with.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧You have a softness and
beneficence <xex>winning on</xex> the hearts of others.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Dryden.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To gain ground on.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The
rabble . . . will in time <xex>win upon</xex> power.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wince</ent>⟦br⟧
